# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rag-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] In data analysis, **cosine similarity** is a measure of similarity between two non-zero vectors defined in an inner product space.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity is the cosine of the angle between the vectors; that is, it is the dot product of the vectors divided by the product of their lengths.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] It follows that the cosine similarity does not depend on the magnitudes of the vectors, but only on their angle.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] The cosine similarity always belongs to the interval $[-1,+1].$ For example, two proportional vectors have a cosine similarity of +1, two orthogonal vectors have a similarity of 0, and two opposite vectors have a similarity of −1.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] In some contexts, the component values of the vectors cannot be negative, in which case the cosine similarity is bounded in $[0,1]$ .
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] For example, in information retrieval and text mining, each word is assigned a different coordinate and a document is represented by the vector of the numbers of occurrences of each word in the document.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity then gives a useful measure of how similar two documents are likely to be, in terms of their subject matter, and independently of the length of the documents.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] The technique is also used to measure cohesion within clusters in the field of data mining.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] One advantage of cosine similarity is its low complexity, especially for sparse vectors: only the non-zero coordinates need to be considered.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] Other names for cosine similarity include **Orchini similarity** and **Tucker coefficient of congruence**; the **Otsuka–Ochiai similarity** (see below) is cosine similarity applied to binary data.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] where $A_{i}$ and $B_{i}$ are the i th components of vectors $\mathbf {A}$ and $\mathbf {B}$ , respectively.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] The resulting similarity ranges from −1 meaning exactly opposite, to +1 meaning exactly the same, with 0 indicating orthogonality (no correlation), while in-between values indicate intermediate similarity or dissimilarity.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] For text matching, the attribute vectors *A* and *B* are usually the term frequency vectors of the documents.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity can be seen as a method of normalizing document length during comparison.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] In the case of information retrieval, the cosine similarity of two documents will range from $0\to 1$ , since the term frequencies cannot be negative.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] This remains true when using TF-IDF weights.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] The angle between two term frequency vectors cannot be greater than 90°.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] If the attribute vectors are normalized by subtracting the vector means (e.g., $A-{\bar {A}}$ ), the measure is called the centered cosine similarity and is equivalent to the Pearson correlation coefficient.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] By virtue of being proportional to squared Euclidean distance, the cosine distance is not a true distance metric; it does not exhibit the triangle inequality property — or, more formally, the Schwarz inequality — and it violates the coincidence axiom.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] To repair the triangle inequality property while maintaining the same ordering, one can convert to Euclidean distance ${\textstyle {\sqrt {2(1-S_{C}(A,B))}}}$ or angular distance *θ* = arccos(*S**C*(*A*, *B*)).
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] Alternatively, the triangular inequality that does work for angular distances can be expressed directly in terms of the cosines; see below.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] The normalized angle, referred to as **angular distance**, between any two vectors A and B is a formal distance metric and can be calculated from the cosine similarity.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] The complement of the angular distance metric can then be used to define **angular similarity** function bounded between 0 and 1, inclusive.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] Unfortunately, computing the inverse cosine (arccos) function is slow, making the use of the angular distance more computationally expensive than using the more common (but not metric) cosine distance above.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] Another effective proxy for cosine distance can be obtained by $L_{2}$ normalisation of the vectors, followed by the application of normal Euclidean distance.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] Using this technique each term in each vector is first divided by the magnitude of the vector, yielding a vector of unit length.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] Once the normalisation has occurred, the vector space can be used with the full range of techniques available to any Euclidean space, notably standard dimensionality reduction techniques.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] This normalised form distance is often used within many deep learning algorithms.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] Here, A and B are sets, and $|A|$ is the number of elements in A .
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] If sets are represented as bit vectors, the Otsuka–Ochiai coefficient can be seen to be the same as the cosine similarity.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] It is identical to the score introduced by Godfrey Thomson.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] In a recent book, the coefficient is tentatively misattributed to another Japanese researcher with the family name Otsuka.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] The confusion arises because in 1957 Akira Ochiai attributes the coefficient only to Otsuka (no first name mentioned) by citing an article by Ikuso Hamai (Japanese: 浜井 生三), who in turn cites the original 1936 article by Yanosuke Otsuka.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] The most noteworthy property of cosine similarity is that it reflects a relative, rather than absolute, comparison of the individual vector dimensions.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] For any positive constant a and vector V , the vectors V and $aV$ are maximally similar.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] The measure is thus most appropriate for data where frequency is more important than absolute values; notably, term frequency in documents.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] However more recent metrics with a grounding in information theory, such as Jensen–Shannon, SED, and triangular divergence have been shown to have improved semantics in at least some contexts.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity is related to Euclidean distance as follows.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] The Euclidean distance is called the *chord distance* (because it is the length of the chord on the unit circle) and it is the Euclidean distance between the vectors which were normalized to unit sum of squared values within them.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] This form of the triangle inequality can be used to bound the minimum and maximum similarity of two objects A and B if the similarities to a reference object C is already known.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] This is used for example in metric data indexing, but has also been used to accelerate spherical k-means clustering the same way the Euclidean triangle inequality has been used to accelerate regular k-means.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] A soft cosine or ("soft" similarity) between two vectors considers similarities between pairs of features.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] For example, in the field of natural language processing (NLP) the similarity among features is quite intuitive.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] Features such as words, *n*-grams, or syntactic *n*-grams can be quite similar, though formally they are considered as different features in the VSM.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] For example, words "play" and "game" are different words and thus mapped to different points in VSM; yet they are semantically related.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] In case of *n*-grams or syntactic *n*-grams, Levenshtein distance can be applied (in fact, Levenshtein distance can be applied to words as well).
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] For calculating soft cosine, the matrix **s** is used to indicate similarity between features.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] It can be calculated through Levenshtein distance, WordNet similarity, or other similarity measures.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] where *sij* = similarity(feature*i*, feature*j*).
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] If there is no similarity between features (*sii* = 1, *sij* = 0 for *i* ≠ *j*), the given equation is equivalent to the conventional cosine similarity formula.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] The time complexity of this measure is quadratic, which makes it applicable to real-world tasks.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] Note that the complexity can be reduced to subquadratic.
[src:rag-systems/cosine-similarity] An efficient implementation of such soft cosine similarity is included in the Gensim open source library.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Formally, the nearest neighbor (NN) search problem is defined as follows: given a set S of points in a space M and a query point $q\in M$ , find the closest point in S to q.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Donald Knuth in volume 3 of *The Art of Computer Programming* (1973) called it the **post-office problem**, referring to an application of assigning to a residence the nearest post office.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] A direct generalization of this problem is a k-NN search, where we need to find the k closest points.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Most commonly M is a metric space and dissimilarity is expressed as a distance metric, which is symmetric and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Even more common, M is taken to be the d-dimensional vector space where dissimilarity is measured using the Euclidean distance, Manhattan distance or other distance metric.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] However, the dissimilarity function can be arbitrary.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] One example is asymmetric Bregman divergence, for which the triangle inequality does not hold.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Various solutions to the NNS problem have been proposed.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The quality and usefulness of the algorithms are determined by the time complexity of queries as well as the space complexity of any search data structures that must be maintained.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The informal observation usually referred to as the curse of dimensionality states that there is no general-purpose exact solution for NNS in high-dimensional Euclidean space using polynomial preprocessing and polylogarithmic search time.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The simplest solution to the NNS problem is to compute the distance from the query point to every other point in the database, keeping track of the "best so far".
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] This algorithm, sometimes referred to as the naive approach, has a running time of *O*(*dN*), where *N* is the cardinality of *S* and *d* is the dimensionality of *S*.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] There are no search data structures to maintain, so the linear search has no space complexity beyond the storage of the database.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Naive search can, on average, outperform space partitioning approaches on higher dimensional spaces.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The absolute distance is not required for distance comparison, only the relative distance.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] In geometric coordinate systems the distance calculation can be sped up considerably by omitting the square root calculation from the distance calculation between two coordinates.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance comparison will still yield identical results.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Since the 1970s, the branch and bound methodology has been applied to the problem.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of Euclidean space, this approach encompasses spatial index or spatial access methods.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Several space-partitioning methods have been developed for solving the NNS problem.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Perhaps the simplest is the k-d tree, which iteratively bisects the search space into two regions containing half of the points of the parent region.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Queries are performed via traversal of the tree from the root to a leaf by evaluating the query point at each split.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Depending on the distance specified in the query, neighboring branches that might contain hits may also need to be evaluated.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] R-trees can yield nearest neighbors not only for Euclidean distance, but can also be used with other distances.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of general metric space, the branch-and-bound approach is known as the metric tree approach.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Particular examples include vp-tree and BK-tree methods.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Using a set of points taken from a 3-dimensional space and put into a BSP tree, and given a query point taken from the same space, a possible solution to the problem of finding the nearest point-cloud point to the query point is given in the following description of an algorithm.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] (Strictly speaking, no such point may exist, because it may not be unique.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] This may not be the case, but it is a good heuristic.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] After having recursively gone through all the trouble of solving the problem for the guessed half-space, now compare the distance returned by this result with the shortest distance from the query point to the partitioning plane.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] This latter distance is that between the query point and the closest possible point that could exist in the half-space not searched.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] If this distance is greater than that returned in the earlier result, then clearly there is no need to search the other half-space.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] If there is such a need, then you must go through the trouble of solving the problem for the other half space, and then compare its result to the former result, and then return the proper result.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] An approximate nearest neighbor search algorithm is allowed to return points whose distance from the query is at most c times the distance from the query to its nearest points.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The appeal of this approach is that, in many cases, an approximate nearest neighbor is almost as good as the exact one.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] In particular, if the distance measure accurately captures the notion of user quality, then small differences in the distance should not matter.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Proximity graph methods (such as navigable small world graphs and HNSW) are considered the current state-of-the-art for the approximate nearest neighbors search.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The methods are based on greedy traversing in proximity neighborhood graphs $G(V,E)$ in which every point $x_{i}\in S$ is uniquely associated with vertex $v_{i}\in V$ .
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The search for the nearest neighbors to a query *q* in the set *S* takes the form of searching for the vertex in the graph $G(V,E)$ .
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The basic algorithm – greedy search – works as follows: search starts from an enter-point vertex $v_{i}\in V$ by computing the distances from the query q to each vertex of its neighborhood $\{v_{j}:(v_{i},v_{j})\in E\}$ , and then finds a vertex with the minimal distance value.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] If the distance value between the query and the selected vertex is smaller than the one between the query and the current element, then the algorithm moves to the selected vertex, and it becomes new enter-point.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The algorithm stops when it reaches a local minimum: a vertex whose neighborhood does not contain a vertex that is closer to the query than the vertex itself.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] These works were preceded by a pioneering paper by Toussaint, in which he introduced the concept of a *relative neighborhood* graph.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Locality sensitive hashing (LSH) is a technique for grouping points in space into 'buckets' based on some distance metric operating on the points.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Points that are close to each other under the chosen metric are mapped to the same bucket with high probability.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The cover tree has a theoretical bound that is based on the dataset's doubling constant.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The bound on search time is *O*(*c*12 log *n*) where *c* is the expansion constant of the dataset.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] In the special case where the data is a dense 3D map of geometric points, the projection geometry of the sensing technique can be used to dramatically simplify the search problem.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] This approach requires that the 3D data is organized by a projection to a two-dimensional grid and assumes that the data is spatially smooth across neighboring grid cells with the exception of object boundaries.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] These assumptions are valid when dealing with 3D sensor data in applications such as surveying, robotics and stereo vision but may not hold for unorganized data in general.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] In practice this technique has an average search time of *O*(*1*) or *O*(*K*) for the *k*-nearest neighbor problem when applied to real world stereo vision data.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] In high-dimensional spaces, tree indexing structures become useless because an increasing percentage of the nodes need to be examined anyway.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] To speed up linear search, a compressed version of the feature vectors stored in RAM is used to prefilter the datasets in a first run.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The final candidates are determined in a second stage using the uncompressed data from the disk for distance calculation.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The VA-file approach is a special case of a compression based search, where each feature component is compressed uniformly and independently.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The optimal compression technique in multidimensional spaces is Vector Quantization (VQ), implemented through clustering.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The database is clustered and the most "promising" clusters are retrieved.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Huge gains over VA-File, tree-based indexes and sequential scan have been observed.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Also note the parallels between clustering and LSH.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] There are numerous variants of the NNS problem and the two most well-known are the *k*-nearest neighbor search and the ε-approximate nearest neighbor search.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] In some applications it may be acceptable to retrieve a "good guess" of the nearest neighbor.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] In those cases, we can use an algorithm which doesn't guarantee to return the actual nearest neighbor in every case, in return for improved speed or memory savings.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Often such an algorithm will find the nearest neighbor in a majority of cases, but this depends strongly on the dataset being queried.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Algorithms that support the approximate nearest neighbor search include locality-sensitive hashing, best bin first and balanced box-decomposition tree based search.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Nearest neighbor distance ratio does not apply the threshold on the direct distance from the original point to the challenger neighbor but on a ratio of it depending on the distance to the previous neighbor.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] It is used in CBIR to retrieve pictures through a "query by example" using the similarity between local features.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] More generally it is involved in several matching problems.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Fixed-radius near neighbors is the problem where one wants to efficiently find all points given in Euclidean space within a given fixed distance from a specified point.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance is assumed to be fixed, but the query point is arbitrary.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] For some applications (e.g. entropy estimation), we may have *N* data-points and wish to know which is the nearest neighbor *for every one of those N points*.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] This could, of course, be achieved by running a nearest-neighbor search once for every point, but an improved strategy would be an algorithm that exploits the information redundancy between these *N* queries to produce a more efficient search.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] As a simple example: when we find the distance from point *X* to point *Y*, that also tells us the distance from point *Y* to point *X*, so the same calculation can be reused in two different queries.
[src:rag-systems/nearest-neighbor-search] Given a fixed dimension, a semi-definite positive norm (thereby including every Lp norm), and *n* points in this space, the nearest neighbour of every point can be found in *O*(*n* log *n*) time and the *m* nearest neighbours of every point can be found in *O*(*mn* log *n*) time.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG improves LLMs by incorporating information retrieval before generating responses.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Unlike LLMs that rely on static training data, RAG pulls relevant text from databases, uploaded documents, or web sources.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG also reduces the need to retrain LLMs with new data, saving on computational and financial costs.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Beyond efficiency gains, RAG also allows LLMs to include sources in their responses, so users can verify the cited sources.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] This provides greater transparency, as users can cross-check retrieved content to ensure accuracy and relevance.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] The term retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) was introduced in a 2020 paper that described combining a parametric language model with a non-parametric external memory accessed through retrieval at inference time.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] For example, when Google first demonstrated its LLM tool "Google Bard" (later re-branded to Gemini), the LLM provided incorrect information about the James Webb Space Telescope.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] This error contributed to a $100 billion decline in Google's stock value.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG is used to prevent these errors, but it does not solve all the problems.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] For example, LLMs can generate misinformation even when pulling from factually correct sources if they misinterpret the context.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] The LLM did not "know" or "understand" the context of the title, generating a false statement.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] LLMs with RAG are programmed to prioritize new information.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] This technique has been called "prompt stuffing." Without prompt stuffing, the LLM's input is generated by a user; with prompt stuffing, additional relevant context is added to this input to guide the model's response.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] This approach provides the LLM with key information early in the prompt, encouraging it to prioritize the supplied data over pre-existing training knowledge.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) enhances large language models (LLMs) by incorporating an information-retrieval mechanism that allows models to access and utilize additional data beyond their original training set.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] *Ars Technica* notes that "when new information becomes available, rather than having to retrain the model, all that's needed is to augment the model's external knowledge base with the updated information" ("augmentation").
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] IBM states that "in the generative phase, the LLM draws from the augmented prompt and its internal representation of its training data to synthesize" an answer.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Typically, the data to be referenced is converted into LLM embeddings, numerical representations in the form of a large vector space.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG can be used on unstructured (usually text), semi-structured, or structured data (for example knowledge graphs).
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] These embeddings are then stored in a vector database to allow for document retrieval.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Given a user query, a document retriever is first called to select the most relevant documents that will be used to augment the query.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] This comparison can be done using a variety of methods, which depend in part on the type of indexing used.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] The model feeds this relevant retrieved information into the LLM via prompt engineering of the user's original query.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Newer implementations (as of 2023) can also incorporate specific augmentation modules with abilities such as expanding queries into multiple domains and using memory and self-improvement to learn from previous retrievals.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Finally, the LLM can generate output based on both the query and the retrieved documents.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Some models incorporate extra steps to improve output, such as the re-ranking of retrieved information, context selection, and fine-tuning.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Retrieval-augmented generation is used in applications where generated responses need to be grounded in external or frequently updated information.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] In healthcare, RAG has been studied as a way to ground large language model outputs in external medical knowledge sources, although reviews have noted continuing challenges around evaluation, ethics, and clinical reliability.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Improvements to the basic process above can be applied at different stages in the RAG flow.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] These methods focus on the encoding of text as either dense or sparse vectors.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Sparse vectors, which encode the identity of a word, are typically dictionary-length and contain mostly zeros.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Dense vectors, which encode meaning, are more compact and contain fewer zeros.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Various enhancements can improve the way similarities are calculated in the vector stores (databases).
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Each Retro block consists of Attention, Chunked Cross Attention, and Feed Forward layers.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Black-lettered boxes show data being changed, and blue lettering shows the algorithm performing the changes.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] By redesigning the language model with the retriever in mind, a 25-time smaller network can get comparable perplexity as its much larger counterparts.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Because it is trained from scratch, this method (Retro) incurs the high cost of training runs that the original RAG scheme avoided.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] The hypothesis is that by giving domain knowledge during training, Retro needs less focus on the domain and can devote its smaller weight resources only to language semantics.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] The redesigned language model is shown here.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] It has been reported that Retro is not reproducible, so modifications were made to make it so.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] The more reproducible version is called Retro++ and includes in-context RAG.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Chunking involves various strategies for breaking up the data into vectors so the retriever can find details in it.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Different data styles have patterns that correct chunking can take advantage of.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Sometimes vector database searches can miss key facts needed to answer a user's question.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] One way to mitigate this is to do a traditional text search, add those results to the text chunks linked to the retrieved vectors from the vector search, and feed the combined hybrid text into the language model for generation.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG does not prevent hallucinations in LLMs.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] While RAG improves the accuracy of large language models (LLMs), it does not eliminate all challenges.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] One limitation is that while RAG reduces the need for frequent model retraining, it does not remove it entirely.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Additionally, LLMs may struggle to recognize when they lack sufficient information to provide a reliable response.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Without specific training, models may generate answers even when they should indicate uncertainty.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] According to IBM, this issue can arise when the model lacks the ability to assess its own knowledge limitations.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] RAG systems may retrieve factually correct but misleading sources, leading to errors in interpretation.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] In some cases, an LLM may extract statements from a source without considering its context, resulting in an incorrect conclusion.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] Additionally, when faced with conflicting information, RAG models may struggle to determine which source is accurate.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] The worst case outcome of this limitation is that the model may combine details from multiple sources producing responses that merge outdated and updated information in a misleading manner.
[src:rag-systems/retrieval-augmented-generation] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, these issues occur because RAG systems may misinterpret the data they retrieve.
[src:rag-systems/semantic-search] Some authors regard semantic search as a set of techniques for retrieving knowledge from richly structured data sources like ontologies and XML as found on the Semantic Web.
[src:rag-systems/semantic-search] Such technologies enable the formal articulation of domain knowledge at a high level of expressiveness and could enable the user to specify their intent in more detail at query time.
[src:rag-systems/semantic-search] The articulation enhances content relevance and depth by including specific places, people, or concepts relevant to the query.
[src:rag-systems/semantic-search] Tools like Google's Knowledge Graph provide structured relationships between entities to enrich query interpretation.
[src:rag-systems/semantic-search] Models like BERT and Sentence-BERT convert words or sentences into dense vectors for similarity comparison.
[src:rag-systems/semantic-search] Semantic ontologies like Web Ontology Language, Resource Description Framework, and Schema.org organize concepts and relationships, allowing systems to infer related terms and deeper meanings.
[src:rag-systems/semantic-search] Hybrid search models combine lexical retrieval (e.g., BM25) with semantic ranking using pretrained transformer models for optimal performance.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] In natural language processing, a **sentence embedding** (or document embedding) is a representation of a natural language text as a vector of numbers which encodes meaningful semantic information.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] The name stems from the initially limitations of the approach to embed sequences of text longer than a sentence, but this is not longer a limitation.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] State of the art embeddings are based on the learned hidden layer representation of dedicated sentence transformer models.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] BERT pioneered an approach involving the use of a dedicated [CLS] token prepended to the beginning of each sentence inputted into the model; the final hidden state vector of this token encodes information about the sentence and can be fine-tuned for use in sentence classification tasks.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] In practice however, BERT's sentence embedding with the [CLS] token achieves poor performance, often worse than simply averaging non-contextual word embeddings.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] SBERT later achieved superior sentence embedding performance by fine tuning BERT's [CLS] token embeddings through the usage of a siamese neural network architecture on the SNLI dataset.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] Other approaches are loosely based on the idea of distributional semantics applied to sentences.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] Skip-Thought trains an encoder-decoder structure for the task of neighboring sentences predictions; this has been shown to achieve worse performance than approaches such as InferSent or SBERT.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] An alternative direction is to aggregate word embeddings, such as those returned by Word2vec, into sentence embeddings.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] The most straightforward approach is to simply compute the average of word vectors, known as continuous bag-of-words (CBOW).
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] However, more elaborate solutions based on word vector quantization have also been proposed.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] One such approach is the vector of locally aggregated word embeddings (VLAWE), which demonstrated performance improvements in downstream text classification tasks.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] In recent years, sentence embedding has seen a growing level of interest due to its applications in natural language queryable knowledge bases through the usage of vector indexing for semantic search.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] LangChain for instance utilizes sentence transformers for purposes of indexing documents.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] In particular, an indexing is generated by generating embeddings for chunks of documents and storing (document chunk, embedding) tuples.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] Then given a query in natural language, the embedding for the query can be generated.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] A top k similarity search algorithm is then used between the query embedding and the document chunk embeddings to retrieve the most relevant document chunks as context information for question answering tasks.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] This approach is also known formally as retrieval-augmented generation.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] Though not as predominant as BERTScore, sentence embeddings are commonly used for sentence similarity evaluation which sees common use for the task of optimizing a Large language model's generation parameters is often performed via comparing candidate sentences against reference sentences.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] By using the cosine-similarity of the sentence embeddings of candidate and reference sentences as the evaluation function, a grid-search algorithm can be utilized to automate hyperparameter optimization.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] Multiple approaches exists for evaluating the quality of sentence embeddings typically covering one or multiple of the use-cases on models.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] Some seek to measure whether the embedding is semantically meaningful by testing if semantically similar sentences appear closer together, while other sentence similarity or if embeddings reflect entailment using corpora such as Sentences Involving Compositional Knowledge (SICK), STS Bencmark.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] Other approaches seek to measure the quality of the embeddings by how well it performs for downstream use-cases such as clustering, classification or semantic search.
[src:rag-systems/sentence-embedding] Comprehensive frameworks such as BEIR or MTEB that encapsulates multiple of these approaches have since become the standard to evaluate the quality of embedding across domains and/or languages.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] A **vector database**, **vector store** or **vector search engine** is a database that stores and retrieves embeddings of data in vector space.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] Vector databases typically implement approximate nearest neighbor algorithms so users can search for records semantically similar to a given input, unlike traditional databases which primarily look up records by exact match.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] Use-cases for vector databases include similarity search, semantic search, multi-modal search, recommendations engines, object detection, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] Vector embeddings are mathematical representations of data in a high-dimensional space.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] In this space, each dimension corresponds to a feature of the data, with the number of dimensions ranging from a few hundred to tens of thousands, depending on the complexity of the data being represented.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] Each data item is represented by one vector in this space.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] Words, phrases, or entire documents, as well as images, audio, and other types of data, can all be vectorized.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] These feature vectors may be computed from the raw data using machine learning methods such as feature extraction algorithms, word embeddings or deep learning networks.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] The goal is that semantically similar data items receive feature vectors close to each other.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] Vector retrieval can be combined with metadata filtering or lexical search to support filtered and hybrid retrieval workflows.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] These techniques may also be combined in vector search systems.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] In recent benchmarks, HNSW-based implementations have been among the best performers.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] Conferences such as the International Conference on Similarity Search and Applications (SISAP) and the Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS) have hosted competitions on vector search in large databases.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] Vector databases are used in a wide range of machine learning applications including similarity search, semantic search, multi-modal search, recommendations engines, object detection, and retrieval-augmented generation.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] An especially common use-case for vector databases is in retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), a method to improve domain-specific responses of large language models.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] The retrieval component of a RAG can be any search system, but is most often implemented as a vector database.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] Text documents describing the domain of interest are collected, and for each document or document section, a feature vector (known as an "embedding") is computed, typically using a deep learning network, and stored in a vector database along with a link to the document.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] Given a user prompt, the feature vector of the prompt is computed, and the database is queried to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:rag-systems/vector-database] These are then automatically added into the context window of the large language model, and the large language model proceeds to create a response to the prompt given this context.
